The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, January 03, 2004 				 Maruti clocks record sales
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 Top gear																								New Delhi, Jan. 2: Maruti Udyog Ltd today reported its best ever December sales, propelled by a production tax cut and low interest rates that spawned attractive finance schemes.																								Maruti Udyog, which is 54.2 per cent owned by Japans Suzuki Motor Corp, said vehicle sales jumped 23.2 per cent from a year ago to 37,091 units. Cumulative sales in the April-December period of the 2003-04 financial year rose 30.3 per cent to 3.28 lakh units. The auto maker, which has a dominating 50 per cent share of the market, has been helped by a cut in production tax in February that allowed all car firms to drop prices by nearly 5 per cent on the sticker price.																								Domestic sales of its Maruti 800, the countrys largest-selling model, rose 12.1 per cent in December to 13,641 units while combined sales of its Omni and Versa vans jumped 18.4 per cent to 4,323 units. 																								It sold 13,918 units of its three compact cars  the Alto, Zen and Wagon R  up 34.6 per cent from the year-ago period. Sales, however, of its Baleno and Esteem sedans surged 42.4 per cent to 1,333 units.																								Sales of Gypsy and Vitara multi-utility vehicles, however, dipped 22.9 per cent to 128 units. 																								The Gurgaon-based company, which revolutionised the domestic car industry after its entry in 1985 with its modern production techniques, was hit by a strike at a key vendor unit in August-September, which hurt production and slowed sales.																								It mainly competes with Tata Motors and the local units of Hyundai, Fiat, Ford. Past financial year to March 2003 it sold 3.62 lakh units. Hyundai sales zoom																								Hyundai Motor Indias car sales surged by 83 per cent in December 2003 to 12,382 units, driven by rising demand for compact car Santro and mid-size model Accent, says PTI.																								Honda Siel Cars Indias sales too surged by 195 per cent in December 2003 to 2,760 units on the back of strong demand for the recently-launched all-new mid-size car City. 
